  "prompt": "How much money will you have to pay to try each and every combination of Subway sandwiches?",
  "response": "To calculate the total cost of trying every combination of Subway sandwiches, we'll need to consider the different elements that can be customized in a Subway sandwich. The main components include:\n\n1. **Bread Types**: Typically, Subway offers several types of bread (e.g., Italian, whole wheat, honey oat, etc.). For this example, let's assume there are 5 types of bread.\n\n2. **Meat Options**: Subway provides a variety of protein options (e.g., turkey, ham, roast beef, chicken, etc.). Let's assume there are 8 meat options.\n\n3. **Vegetables**: Customers can choose from a range of vegetables (e.g., lettuce, tomatoes, onions, green peppers, etc.). Let's assume there are 10 vegetable options, and you can choose any combination of them.\n\n4. **Cheese Options**: Typically, there are around 5 cheese options. \n\n5. **Condiments**: Subway offers various sauces and condiments (e.g., mayonnaise, mustard, vinaigrette, etc.). Let's assume there are 5 condiment options.\n\nNow let's calculate the combinations:\n\n1. **Bread**: 5 types\n2. **Meat**: 8 types\n3. **Vegetables**: Assuming you can choose 0 to all 10 vegetables, the total combinations of vegetables is \\(2^{10} - 1\\) (subtracting 1 to exclude the case of choosing none).\n4. **Cheese**: 5 types (assuming you can either have it or not, so \\(2^5 - 1\\) for at least one cheese).\n5. **Condiments**: Assuming you can choose 0 to all 5 condiments, it's \\(2^5 - 1\\) for at least one condiment.\n\nNow we can calculate:\n\n- Combinations of Vegetables = \\(2^{10} - 1 = 1024 - 1 = 1023\\)\n- Combinations of Cheese = \\(2^5 - 1 = 32 - 1 = 31\\)\n- Combinations of Condiments = \\(2^5 - 1 = 32 - 1 = 31\\)\n\nNow multiplying these together:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Total combinations} = \\text{Bread} \\times \\text{Meat} \\times \\text{Vegetables} \\times \\text{Cheese} \\times \\text{Condiments}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n= 5 \\times 8 \\times 1023 \\times 31 \\times 31\n\\]\n\nCalculating this gives:\n\n- First, calculate \\(31 \\times 31 = 961\\).\n- Then calculate \\(8 \\times 5 = 40\\).\n- Now, \\(40 \\times 1023 = 40920\\).\n- Finally, multiply \\(40920 \\times 961\\).\n\nCalculating the last multiplication yields: \n\\[ \n40920 \\times 961 \\approx 39,244,920\n\\]\n\nSo, approximately 39,244,920 combinations of Subway sandwiches.\n\n**Cost Calculation**:\nIf we assume that each sandwich costs an average of $6, the total cost would be:\n\n\\[\n39,244,920 \\text{ combinations} \\times 6 \\text{ dollars/sandwich} \\approx 235,469,520 \\text{ dollars}\n\\]\n\nThus, you would need to pay approximately **$235,469,520** to try each and every combination of Subway sandwiches based on the assumptions made.",
